hese discounted deals, a meagre&nbsp;55,000 homes have signed up. That's just 1.2 percent of those eligible, Ofcom research shows.</p><p>So, if you live in one of the&nbsp;4.2 million households eligible for a&nbsp;"Social Tariff", we'd recommend signing up for BT's Home Essentials plan. It includes&nbsp;<a data-link-tracking="InArticle|Link" href="https://www.awin1.com/cread.php?awinmid=3041&amp;awinaffid=213635&amp;clickref=Express---ExpressTech-&amp;ued=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bt.com%2Fexp%2Fbroadband%2Fhome-essentials" target="_blank" rel="nofollow" onclick="ExpressApp.GoogleAnalytics.TrackEvent('Affiliate NetworkEvent', 'AWIN')"><strong>average 67Mbps download speeds and 700 minutes of calls from the landline for &pound;15 a month</strong></a>.&nbsp;For comparison, BT charges &pound;32.99 a month for its Full Fibre 2 bundle, which offers average download speeds of 74Mbps. So, Universal Credit claimants will benefit from some hefty savings &ndash; around &pound;17.99 a month, or over &pound;215 over the course of a year. And the benefits don't end there.</p><p>BT will&nbsp;<em>never</em>&nbsp;charge an early exit fee if your circumstances change, so you can leave within the 12-month minimum contract term and not worry about any extra charges. That's different to every other&nbsp;broadband deal available from BT.</p></div><div class="partners-element single"><div class="widget blurb" data-expires="" data-alt-exp-text="" data-id="12129" data-name="BT Home Essentials"><div class="data"><div class="images"> <a href="https://www.awin1.com/cread.php?awinmid=3041&awinaffid=213635&clickref=Express---ExpressTech-&ued=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bt.com%2Fexp%2Fbroadband%2Fhome-essentials" target="_blank" onclick="ExpressApp.GoogleAnalytics.TrackEvent('Affiliate widget', 'BT Home Essentials')"> <picture> <source srcset="https://cdn.images.express.co.uk/img/dynamic/affiliateswidgets/175x108/1663947880575.avif" type="image/avif"> <source srcset="https://cdn.images.express.co.uk/img/dynamic/